1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
https://slama.dev/comeback/

2
00:00:03,850 --> 00:00:08,650
Yeah, ABBA, well, they can always lift your spirits.

3
00:00:09,280 --> 00:00:10,000
Not today.

4
00:00:11,150 --> 00:00:15,710
Good God, what has Ozzak done to you this time?

5
00:00:16,050 --> 00:00:17,550
Did he call you a mollusk again?

6
00:00:19,150 --> 00:00:21,240
You mean old clam?

7
00:00:21,850 --> 00:00:24,850
No, Ozzak is exceptionally innocent this time.

8
00:00:25,750 --> 00:00:28,150
I'm having a terrible day.

9
00:00:59,050 --> 00:01:03,670
This morning Zoran took my car because they're installing bulletproof glass in his.

10
00:01:03,670 --> 00:01:05,010
I thought he already had them.

11
00:01:05,850 --> 00:01:08,150
He thought so too until Tuesday.

12
00:01:08,950 --> 00:01:13,150
So I had to take the metro, but I accidentally bought a child's ticket and got caught by an inspector.

13
00:01:13,150 --> 00:01:14,110
Did you get a fine?

14
00:01:14,650 --> 00:01:15,850
Forget the fine.

15
00:01:15,850 --> 00:01:20,550
He told me if I think I look fifteen, I belong in a nuthouse, not on an escalator.

16
00:01:20,550 --> 00:01:22,590
And at the deli?

17
00:01:26,550 --> 00:01:27,550
At the deli?

18
00:01:27,730 --> 00:01:32,010
They packed me garlic paste instead of the grain sprout salad.

19
00:01:32,250 --> 00:01:36,770
I noticed at the register and the woman said take it or leave it and stop holding up the line.

20
00:01:37,210 --> 00:01:38,690
I can tell you took the paste.

21
00:01:43,140 --> 00:01:44,700
But that's over now.

22
00:01:44,920 --> 00:01:46,560
I'm no...

23
00:01:46,560 --> 00:01:47,120
Pushover.

24
00:01:47,960 --> 00:01:48,560
...pencil sharpener.

25
00:01:53,150 --> 00:01:55,740
Creative Conflict course by Dr. Stehno?

26
00:01:56,050 --> 00:01:58,540
It was in Perfect Woman magazine, I've already signed up.

27
00:01:58,550 --> 00:02:01,500
Become a communication ninja?

28
00:02:01,550 --> 00:02:04,680
Handle anyone in fifteen lessons?

29
00:02:04,680 --> 00:02:07,500
I had no idea you could learn that.

30
00:02:07,680 --> 00:02:09,580
That would help me handle Ozzak.

31
00:02:10,650 --> 00:02:11,450
Where is he anyway?

32
00:02:11,530 --> 00:02:12,690
Sleeping in the closet.

33
00:02:13,160 --> 00:02:15,120
He hid as soon as I put on Mamma Mia.

34
00:02:15,560 --> 00:02:17,120
Don't worry, Marcelka, I'll handle him.

35
00:02:17,440 --> 00:02:18,000
Ozzak!

36
00:02:18,120 --> 00:02:19,640
Tomas, leave him be.

37
00:02:20,650 --> 00:02:21,950
It's in me.

38
00:02:22,350 --> 00:02:24,700
I filled out the entrance test and I got banana.

39
00:02:24,700 --> 00:02:25,160
How?

40
00:02:26,250 --> 00:02:28,520
Those are personality types according to Michurin.

41
00:02:28,520 --> 00:02:29,600
Banana is the softest.

42
00:02:30,950 --> 00:02:32,880
You can't believe such nonsense.

43
00:02:32,880 --> 00:02:34,060
Come on, Ozzak!

44
00:02:39,250 --> 00:02:40,450
And who did that to you?

45
00:02:40,530 --> 00:02:41,870
The barber, a month ago.

46
00:02:42,090 --> 00:02:42,970
What did you do to upset him?

47
00:02:43,090 --> 00:02:44,150
Don't get into that now, drop it!

48
00:02:46,150 --> 00:02:50,280
Bro, how many times have I told you I don't want you leaving Marcelka alone at the counter?

49
00:02:50,280 --> 00:02:52,220
And the old pepper tattled again, huh?

50
00:02:53,810 --> 00:02:55,610
How dare you talk about Marcelka like that?

51
00:02:56,130 --> 00:02:56,650
She didn't complain.

52
00:02:56,830 --> 00:02:58,550
Right, but she's not a pepper, she's a ba...

53
00:03:00,150 --> 00:03:01,550
Your colleague.

54
00:03:01,630 --> 00:03:03,370
You're simply going to treat her with respect.

55
00:03:03,410 --> 00:03:05,030
You're not going to take advantage of the fact that she's soft.

56
00:03:05,410 --> 00:03:06,790
Please stop defending me.

57
00:03:06,950 --> 00:03:08,010
But I meant well.

58
00:03:08,370 --> 00:03:10,010
So can I go back now?

59
00:03:10,750 --> 00:03:13,250
You know what, sort it out between yourselves.

60
00:03:13,410 --> 00:03:14,170
Wait, come here.

61
00:03:14,850 --> 00:03:15,650
Here's a letter for you.

62
00:03:16,430 --> 00:03:17,170
Prase is writing?

63
00:03:17,170 --> 00:03:20,130
Hmm, I'd be surprised, he always writes everything on beer coasters.

64
00:03:20,130 --> 00:03:20,550
Prase?

65
00:03:21,150 --> 00:03:23,050
Yeah, Ozzak's best friend.

66
00:03:23,050 --> 00:03:26,450
He always promised to send him a coaster from every city where he had a beer.

67
00:03:27,050 --> 00:03:28,350
The stroller room is full of them.

68
00:03:28,550 --> 00:03:31,550
If anyone has a baby, there'll be trouble.

69
00:03:33,890 --> 00:03:34,510
What is it?

70
00:03:35,250 --> 00:03:36,650
The bartender from Marik's is writing.

71
00:03:38,850 --> 00:03:40,250
Prase is dead.

72
00:03:45,050 --> 00:03:47,970
Just two weeks ago he wrote from Iceland that he was coming home.

73
00:03:47,970 --> 00:03:48,410
Really?

74
00:03:48,890 --> 00:03:50,450
I don't remember a coaster from Iceland.

75
00:03:50,450 --> 00:03:53,050
Because the mail lady refused to put it in her bag.

76
00:03:53,450 --> 00:03:56,150
It was big and smelled a bit, you know.

77
00:03:56,850 --> 00:03:58,450
So I had to go to the post office.

78
00:04:01,650 --> 00:04:15,350
Libal writes that he arrived a minute after opening, had his fourteen pints, praised the beer, said in Iceland they serve piss because glaciers may be great for cooling but you can't replace hops with lichen.

79
00:04:16,150 --> 00:04:18,250
He finished his drink and that was it.

80
00:04:20,350 --> 00:04:21,250
A beautiful death.

81
00:04:23,050 --> 00:04:24,450
Yeah, Prase knew how to live.

82
00:04:25,150 --> 00:04:25,950
And how to die.

83
00:04:25,970 --> 00:04:26,550
Indeed.

84
00:04:27,550 --> 00:04:28,250
To Prase.

85
00:04:29,750 --> 00:04:31,930
These pub nicknames are terrible.

86
00:04:32,010 --> 00:04:34,410
How can Ozzak call someone Prase at a time like this?

87
00:04:34,430 --> 00:04:35,070
That's cruel.

88
00:04:35,350 --> 00:04:36,650
But his name was Prase.

89
00:04:37,280 --> 00:04:38,980
I thought his nickname was Abortion.

90
00:04:39,160 --> 00:04:40,480
But Ozzak banned it.

91
00:04:40,950 --> 00:04:42,350
He thought it was cruel.

92
00:04:43,550 --> 00:04:45,290
Bro, where was Prase's name Prase?

93
00:04:45,650 --> 00:04:46,350
Of course.

94
00:04:46,990 --> 00:04:48,250
It must be a blow for him.

95
00:04:48,370 --> 00:04:50,030
He and Prase were practically twins.

96
00:04:50,610 --> 00:04:51,770
If you don't believe me, take a look.

97
00:04:54,050 --> 00:04:57,350
Ozzak, why are they sending you an ID card?

98
00:04:57,950 --> 00:05:00,250
Ludek Prase Pacovsky?

99
00:05:01,450 --> 00:05:02,330
How Pacovsky?

100
00:05:02,950 --> 00:05:09,550
Well, bro, you know, I kind of forgot to tell you, but I adopted him.

101
00:05:11,450 --> 00:05:12,390
What kind of nonsense is that?

102
00:05:12,390 --> 00:05:15,290
When you were singing that awful disco, I just missed having a brother.

103
00:05:15,690 --> 00:05:17,810
Adults can't adopt each other.

104
00:05:18,150 --> 00:05:19,350
Why not?

105
00:05:20,050 --> 00:05:23,050
Old Houba would write anything into the registry for three bottles of rum.

106
00:05:23,620 --> 00:05:24,060
Appalling.

107
00:05:24,550 --> 00:05:26,750
No wonder they called him Mushroom, being that way.

108
00:05:26,950 --> 00:05:28,520
Houba's name was Houba.

109
00:05:28,520 --> 00:05:29,760
Ondrej Was-For-Houbova.

110
00:05:29,780 --> 00:05:30,940
Friendly building league.

111
00:05:38,550 --> 00:05:39,580
What are you doing here?

112
00:05:39,750 --> 00:05:41,820
I thought we were working on the report together.

113
00:05:41,820 --> 00:05:44,940
I wonder how a half-wit like you could help me with it.

114
00:05:45,040 --> 00:05:46,860
Yeah, I'm not in the mood for this now.

115
00:05:46,960 --> 00:05:49,420
Well, I'm not in the mood to get punished because of this.

116
00:05:49,440 --> 00:05:50,920
But I said I'd help you.

117
00:05:52,250 --> 00:05:52,950
Let's see then.

118
00:05:52,990 --> 00:05:54,750
What was the name of the ancient heroine?

119
00:05:54,750 --> 00:05:59,150
Daughter and sister of Oedipus, who buried her slain brother even though it was forbidden.

120
00:05:59,330 --> 00:05:59,770
Antigone.

121
00:05:59,770 --> 00:06:01,350
Even she knows that.

122
00:06:03,290 --> 00:06:05,090
And do you know what Lexa said during the exam?

123
00:06:05,210 --> 00:06:06,590
Even though Sasa was whispering the answer.

124
00:06:07,550 --> 00:06:08,950
She mumbles so badly though.

125
00:06:10,150 --> 00:06:10,590
Antigynda!

126
00:06:13,050 --> 00:06:15,450
If you hadn't laughed so stupidly, nothing would have happened.

127
00:06:15,850 --> 00:06:18,350
If you hadn't called me stupid, nothing would have happened.

128
00:06:18,710 --> 00:06:21,210
If you hadn't called me an idiot, I wouldn't have thrown the sponge at you.

129
00:06:21,330 --> 00:06:23,630
If you hadn't ducked so badly, the teacher wouldn't have gotten hit.

130
00:06:23,710 --> 00:06:24,010
Enough!

131
00:06:24,650 --> 00:06:26,850
I'm not going to listen to this when the family is in crisis.

132
00:06:27,150 --> 00:06:29,350
You say that even when the juice runs out.

133
00:06:30,650 --> 00:06:31,650
Don't trivialize this.

134
00:06:32,150 --> 00:06:37,650
Your irresponsible uncle infiltrated the family with a person named Prase who just died.

135
00:06:38,450 --> 00:06:39,450
That's unbelievable.

136
00:06:40,050 --> 00:06:44,290
Though since the time he came and said his friend Sycak would be living with us, nothing surprises me.

137
00:06:44,290 --> 00:06:45,650
Who had a problem with Sycak?

138
00:06:46,450 --> 00:06:49,850
He was clean, quiet, didn't eat much and just slept all the time.

139
00:06:49,850 --> 00:06:53,750
Tomas, was Sycak a last name or a nickname?

140
00:06:54,550 --> 00:06:55,350
It was a snake.

141
00:07:03,760 --> 00:07:04,360
Hello.

142
00:07:04,700 --> 00:07:05,340
Ah, hello.

143
00:07:06,150 --> 00:07:08,240
Have you been to that creative conflict course?

144
00:07:08,240 --> 00:07:09,040
Do you have a problem with that?

145
00:07:09,450 --> 00:07:12,750
Why would I have a problem with that?

146
00:07:13,040 --> 00:07:14,920
Answering a question with a question is pathetic.

147
00:07:14,920 --> 00:07:18,400
But you also answered my question with a question.

148
00:07:18,850 --> 00:07:21,650
Big deal with such a trivial thing.

149
00:07:22,950 --> 00:07:24,650
I used trivialization.

150
00:07:24,840 --> 00:07:26,180
Stehno is right.

151
00:07:26,180 --> 00:07:29,360
Trivializing your opponent confuses them perfectly.

152
00:07:29,360 --> 00:07:29,820
Right?

153
00:07:30,260 --> 00:07:30,980
No.

154
00:07:32,950 --> 00:07:35,040
Tomas, that course completely changed my life.

155
00:07:35,350 --> 00:07:37,000
Zoran gave me back my car.

156
00:07:37,450 --> 00:07:38,550
Of his own accord?

157
00:07:38,920 --> 00:07:39,920
Of his own accord.

158
00:07:39,980 --> 00:07:41,040
I demanded it.

159
00:07:41,160 --> 00:07:43,220
He yelled at me that I'm a spoiled hysteric.

160
00:07:43,280 --> 00:07:46,320
So I told him he's a deranged Albanian and he should take a taxi.

161
00:07:47,850 --> 00:07:50,850
Stehno completely changed my view of social interaction.

162
00:07:51,650 --> 00:07:52,880
It would do you good too.

163
00:07:52,880 --> 00:07:54,200
And why do you think?

164
00:07:56,050 --> 00:07:57,870
Your eternal conflicts with your brother.

165
00:07:58,150 --> 00:07:59,750
You handle them like an amateur.

166
00:07:59,950 --> 00:08:02,050
Even Stehno is no match for Ozzak.

167
00:08:02,350 --> 00:08:04,050
Stehno can handle the impossible.

168
00:08:04,050 --> 00:08:06,470
Today they accepted my complaint at the Vietnamese market.

169
00:08:06,550 --> 00:08:07,750
I don't believe that.

170
00:08:07,830 --> 00:08:08,190
But yes.

171
00:08:08,690 --> 00:08:10,710
All it took was a little controlled aggression.

172
00:08:10,770 --> 00:08:11,070
What's that?

173
00:08:11,650 --> 00:08:12,650
You do it like this.

174
00:08:13,350 --> 00:08:16,350
You look them in the eye and say very calmly.

175
00:08:18,250 --> 00:08:21,450
If you keep pretending you don't speak Czech, I'll set fire to your stand.

176
00:08:22,550 --> 00:08:27,150
He gave me my money back and threw in a towel with Sandokan on it.

177
00:08:29,150 --> 00:08:31,750
Fine, so what does Stehno say I'm doing wrong?

178
00:08:32,850 --> 00:08:35,950
Well, when he does something wrong, you turn red and start yelling.

179
00:08:36,060 --> 00:08:36,740
Ozzak!

180
00:08:37,340 --> 00:08:38,620
And that's wrong?

181
00:08:38,860 --> 00:08:39,300
Yes!

182
00:08:40,250 --> 00:08:41,150
Stehno says, he who shrieks, won't convince.

183
00:08:43,320 --> 00:08:46,860
Be firm, yes, but don't forget to hear him out.

184
00:08:47,280 --> 00:08:51,380
Explain where he went wrong and back your arguments with a threat.

185
00:08:52,250 --> 00:08:56,850
But careful, you must be able to follow through, otherwise the conflict will repeat.

186
00:09:01,350 --> 00:09:03,250
Ozzak, where have you been?

187
00:09:03,350 --> 00:09:06,640
Work starts at 8:30, it's already noon.

188
00:09:06,640 --> 00:09:07,340
At the Badger!

189
00:09:08,150 --> 00:09:11,850
Simona tapped a dark one and we held a minute of silence for the deceased.

190
00:09:12,150 --> 00:09:13,350
I managed to down three.

191
00:09:20,950 --> 00:09:27,120
I told you that if you don't follow work hours, I'll stop paying your tab at the Badger.

192
00:09:27,550 --> 00:09:31,350
To me, sure, but you wouldn't say that to Simona's face, would you?

193
00:09:31,400 --> 00:09:32,380
Ozzak...

194
00:09:33,550 --> 00:09:37,100
Fine, so you'll cover for Marcelka this afternoon.

195
00:09:37,100 --> 00:09:38,040
Unfortunately that won't work.

196
00:09:38,200 --> 00:09:38,940
I gotta run.

197
00:09:39,550 --> 00:09:41,350
And what's so important that you have to do?

198
00:09:41,550 --> 00:09:42,750
I'm arranging the funeral.

199
00:09:43,250 --> 00:09:45,660
Libal told him they'll keep Prase in the cooler until Monday at most.

200
00:09:45,660 --> 00:09:46,680
After that the health inspector comes.

201
00:09:48,750 --> 00:09:51,750
Yeah, and I told the guys we'd pay for the funeral.

202
00:09:52,250 --> 00:09:53,750
He was family after all, right?

203
00:09:56,490 --> 00:09:56,890
Ozzak!

204
00:10:04,150 --> 00:10:07,550
Antigone must have really loved her brother to risk her neck for him.

205
00:10:08,350 --> 00:10:11,160
I wonder what she would have done if her brother was Ozzak.

206
00:10:11,160 --> 00:10:11,760
What did he do?

207
00:10:12,450 --> 00:10:14,350
He dragged a stranger into our family.

208
00:10:14,850 --> 00:10:15,750
Dad was furious.

209
00:10:15,950 --> 00:10:19,150
That's how furious Mom was when I brought home a stray kitten.

210
00:10:19,350 --> 00:10:21,250
It was gone the next day.

211
00:10:22,350 --> 00:10:25,250
I sometimes think she flushed it down the toilet.

212
00:10:25,950 --> 00:10:26,750
She didn't.

213
00:10:26,850 --> 00:10:27,750
How do you know?

214
00:10:28,750 --> 00:10:33,140
Well, let's not get into the details, but maybe you could try again.

215
00:10:33,140 --> 00:10:34,100
Sycak is already out of the house.

216
00:10:35,060 --> 00:10:35,940
Lunch again.

217
00:10:38,750 --> 00:10:39,950
What are you pouting about?

218
00:10:40,310 --> 00:10:42,010
Fat noodles again.

219
00:10:43,010 --> 00:10:44,790
I know you're gonna just pick at it again.

220
00:10:46,150 --> 00:10:49,350
Auntie, are you also mourning that Prase guy?

221
00:10:50,250 --> 00:10:51,350
Of course, he was a great guy.

222
00:10:52,150 --> 00:10:53,350
That's what Ozzak says too.

223
00:10:53,550 --> 00:10:54,850
You don't remember him?

224
00:10:55,490 --> 00:10:55,890
No.

225
00:10:56,450 --> 00:10:57,910
Even though he practically raised you?

226
00:10:57,910 --> 00:10:58,310
Really?

227
00:10:58,410 --> 00:10:58,830
Of course.

228
00:10:59,850 --> 00:11:01,450
Probably Sasa and Lexa too.

229
00:11:01,750 --> 00:11:04,760
Whenever I came home, they were fed, washed and in bed, so...

230
00:11:05,350 --> 00:11:07,350
Either the building manager or Prase.

231
00:11:07,450 --> 00:11:10,100
Wasn't he the guy who blew his nose into my sock?

232
00:11:10,100 --> 00:11:10,920
Of course.

233
00:11:11,650 --> 00:11:12,450
Poor guy.

234
00:11:12,850 --> 00:11:15,050
He was allergic to baby powder.

235
00:11:15,750 --> 00:11:17,790
But it's impossible that you don't remember him.

236
00:11:17,790 --> 00:11:18,910
Really, not a clue.

237
00:11:19,450 --> 00:11:23,650
Whenever Tomas went on tour, you were here with Prase and Ozzak all the time.

238
00:11:24,250 --> 00:11:28,090
Prase even made you a play corner under the tap, packed with toys.

239
00:11:28,090 --> 00:11:29,730
So Ozzak bought me toys?

240
00:11:29,890 --> 00:11:30,990
No, they made them for you.

241
00:11:31,650 --> 00:11:34,250
You absolutely loved that five-liter jar with the pickled sausage.

242
00:11:34,850 --> 00:11:37,040
You played aquarium with it all day long.

243
00:11:37,350 --> 00:11:41,580
No, that's nonsense, because I clearly remember having a real aquarium.

244
00:11:41,580 --> 00:11:42,060
Really?

245
00:11:42,750 --> 00:11:46,550
Yeah, I had two fish in it, they were called Little Sausage and Smoked Meat.

246
00:11:50,950 --> 00:11:54,740
But wait, I remember clearly they were fish, they had little fins.

247
00:11:55,050 --> 00:11:56,050
That was the onion garnish.

248
00:12:03,450 --> 00:12:04,550
Simona, we need to talk.

249
00:12:04,950 --> 00:12:07,050
Go ahead, vent, I'm used to it.

250
00:12:08,850 --> 00:12:14,270
So I went to the registry office and guess what, Prase is actually registered as Ozzak's and my brother.

251
00:12:14,650 --> 00:12:16,210
You could always count on Houba.

252
00:12:16,650 --> 00:12:18,050
That's to be expected from him.

253
00:12:18,850 --> 00:12:20,450
But you know what really surprised me?

254
00:12:21,150 --> 00:12:23,050
Our sister is registered there too.

255
00:12:23,550 --> 00:12:25,450
Simona Bucek Pacovska.

256
00:12:28,750 --> 00:12:30,250
What were you trying to do?

257
00:12:31,550 --> 00:12:34,750
I figured if something happened to me and Libor was back in prison,

258
00:12:34,850 --> 00:12:36,550
you could take care of the kids.

259
00:12:36,830 --> 00:12:37,230
What?

260
00:12:37,950 --> 00:12:41,250
And seeing how you treat your dead brother, I wouldn't even entrust them to you.

261
00:12:42,450 --> 00:12:45,800
If I hear one more time that Prase was my brother, I won't be held responsible!

262
00:12:45,800 --> 00:12:46,720
You should be proud.

263
00:12:46,940 --> 00:12:47,920
Are you kidding me?

264
00:12:48,350 --> 00:12:49,250
He was flawless.

265
00:12:50,250 --> 00:12:51,350
Except for the name.

266
00:12:52,850 --> 00:12:55,450
When I was young I married him, but I didn't want to be called Mrs. Prase.

267
00:12:57,090 --> 00:12:57,490
Right.

268
00:12:58,070 --> 00:12:59,470
Could you sign this for me?

269
00:12:59,630 --> 00:13:00,090
What is it?

270
00:13:01,650 --> 00:13:03,450
Material liability?

271
00:13:03,650 --> 00:13:06,450
I need to cover myself in case something gets broken at the party.

272
00:13:06,650 --> 00:13:08,550
Ozzak invited all his old buddies.

273
00:13:09,050 --> 00:13:10,570
And how's he planning to pay for it?

274
00:13:10,570 --> 00:13:11,290
What do you mean?

275
00:13:11,950 --> 00:13:12,950
Same as always.

276
00:13:14,850 --> 00:13:15,550
What is it?

277
00:13:17,550 --> 00:13:19,150
I'm not paying for anything.

278
00:13:20,850 --> 00:13:22,130
You want to be cheap about a dead person.

279
00:13:22,350 --> 00:13:24,150
Penny-pinching on your own family like this.

280
00:13:24,750 --> 00:13:28,270
As for the family, for tomorrow get me five bottles of rum ready.

281
00:13:29,550 --> 00:13:30,530
Well, that's more like it.

282
00:13:30,950 --> 00:13:32,350
Are you sure about the rum?

283
00:13:32,750 --> 00:13:35,870
Prase used to say rum is a woman's drink, that real men drink draft spirits.

284
00:13:37,150 --> 00:13:39,250
That rum is for the registry office.

285
00:13:41,750 --> 00:13:43,450
Houbova has gotten quite ambitious.

286
00:13:48,250 --> 00:13:50,250
So let's recap.

287
00:13:50,450 --> 00:14:01,580
Hop wreaths, peony flowers, glass coffin.

288
00:14:01,950 --> 00:14:02,580
With a handle.

289
00:14:02,850 --> 00:14:13,260
And then there's your request for the deceased to be accompanied on his last journey by the band Brutus.

290
00:14:14,150 --> 00:14:15,650
Unfortunately that's not possible.

291
00:14:16,050 --> 00:14:16,550
Why?

292
00:14:16,850 --> 00:14:20,680
For these purposes we have a contracted trained singer, Mrs. Marta.

293
00:14:20,680 --> 00:14:23,180
She's a true artist, a beautiful alto.

294
00:14:23,780 --> 00:14:25,760
And the director's wife.

295
00:14:26,420 --> 00:14:28,460
But Prase would have wanted the Brutus guys.

296
00:14:28,960 --> 00:14:31,800
I tried to explain this to the director.

297
00:14:31,940 --> 00:14:34,000
His decision stands.

298
00:14:34,000 --> 00:14:45,650
However, he unofficially suggested that if you contact Mrs. Marta directly and she agrees to learn the song "Let's Get Drunk" instead of her favorite...

299
00:14:45,650 --> 00:14:47,170
The Lord Is My Shepherd.

300
00:14:48,050 --> 00:14:50,150
He won't object either.

301
00:14:50,450 --> 00:14:53,350
Mrs. Marta has considerable influence over the agency.

302
00:14:54,150 --> 00:14:57,650
But that's just my private observation.

303
00:15:00,650 --> 00:15:04,420
Bro, quickly say goodbye to your pal here, we need to talk.

304
00:15:04,850 --> 00:15:06,650
This is Mr. Tichy from the funeral home.

305
00:15:07,080 --> 00:15:07,700
Hello.

306
00:15:09,850 --> 00:15:11,750
And why is he dressed like Mitch Buchannon?

307
00:15:13,950 --> 00:15:16,150
The director insists on it.

308
00:15:16,550 --> 00:15:18,850
The company motto is the Mona Lisa.

309
00:15:18,910 --> 00:15:21,890
Our reward is a smile on the faces of the bereaved.

310
00:15:21,890 --> 00:15:26,050
And according to him, black unnecessarily depresses the mourners.

311
00:15:26,250 --> 00:15:28,650
And what do you want here?

312
00:15:29,150 --> 00:15:33,350
I'm discussing the funeral details of your brother with your brother here.

313
00:15:33,350 --> 00:15:35,550
That's not my brother.

314
00:15:36,350 --> 00:15:37,460
You're not his brother?

315
00:15:37,850 --> 00:15:38,720
Of course I am.

316
00:15:38,720 --> 00:15:39,540
The other one.

317
00:15:39,620 --> 00:15:40,360
Damn it, bro.

318
00:15:40,970 --> 00:15:42,230
But you are the brother of the deceased?

319
00:15:42,230 --> 00:15:44,470
Sure, but not for long.

320
00:15:44,470 --> 00:15:47,030
Tomorrow I'm going to Houba and this whole registry circus ends.

321
00:15:47,030 --> 00:15:50,750
And I won't pay for the funeral, or the reception, or anything.

322
00:15:50,950 --> 00:15:52,570
After everything Prase did for us?

323
00:15:52,570 --> 00:15:53,070
Yeah, so what?

324
00:15:53,570 --> 00:15:54,270
Lots of things.

325
00:15:54,430 --> 00:15:55,110
Name one.

326
00:15:56,450 --> 00:15:57,450
Fine, as you wish.

327
00:15:57,640 --> 00:15:59,940
Remember when I brought Ivuska from kindergarten and she was soaking wet?

328
00:15:59,960 --> 00:16:00,720
I said it was raining?

329
00:16:00,840 --> 00:16:01,160
Yeah.

330
00:16:01,320 --> 00:16:02,140
Well it wasn't raining!

331
00:16:02,750 --> 00:16:06,650
Prase pulled her out of the fountain she fell into while fishing for my beer money.

332
00:16:06,940 --> 00:16:07,920
Ozzak!

333
00:16:09,200 --> 00:16:12,040
I'll take my leave now.

334
00:16:12,260 --> 00:16:16,300
I'm sure you'll want to cope with your grief in private.

335
00:16:16,400 --> 00:16:19,560
Five bottles of rum will cure my grief.

336
00:16:21,850 --> 00:16:22,350
Man.

337
00:16:28,250 --> 00:16:29,950
This isn't a book, this is a madhouse.

338
00:16:30,350 --> 00:16:32,350
For kids it's actually quite interesting.

339
00:16:32,390 --> 00:16:33,050
Interesting?

340
00:16:33,050 --> 00:16:34,390
It's not normal.

341
00:16:34,650 --> 00:16:36,530
Her dad is also her brother.

342
00:16:36,530 --> 00:16:38,050
That confuses me a little too.

343
00:16:38,590 --> 00:16:40,230
It only confuses you a little?

344
00:16:40,510 --> 00:16:40,950
Yeah.

345
00:16:41,950 --> 00:16:47,930
But mostly I'm confused about why Antigone buries the brother who isn't her father when she knows it's forbidden.

346
00:16:48,050 --> 00:16:50,570
Wait, that's the one thing I understand, it's written there.

347
00:16:50,650 --> 00:16:52,110
Because he'd otherwise never find peace.

348
00:16:52,350 --> 00:16:55,850
But that's his punishment, he attacked their city.

349
00:16:56,450 --> 00:16:59,750
I don't get why Antigone has such a problem burying her brother.

350
00:17:00,360 --> 00:17:00,760
Shut up.

351
00:17:03,950 --> 00:17:05,400
Why does she make such a fuss about it?

352
00:17:05,650 --> 00:17:07,350
Probably because it's forbidden.

353
00:17:07,950 --> 00:17:09,650
But you'd bury me without hesitation, right?

354
00:17:10,080 --> 00:17:10,440
No.

355
00:17:11,950 --> 00:17:12,330
Why not?

356
00:17:12,550 --> 00:17:14,050
Well, if it was forbidden.

357
00:17:14,350 --> 00:17:16,320
But if I needed it, you'd bury me, right?

358
00:17:16,320 --> 00:17:16,560
No.

359
00:17:17,150 --> 00:17:18,050
Sis, cut it out.

360
00:17:18,080 --> 00:17:19,040
Lexa, stop it.

361
00:17:19,320 --> 00:17:20,140
Lexa, stop it.

362
00:17:20,340 --> 00:17:22,560
When you need burying, come to me.

363
00:17:22,620 --> 00:17:23,340
See, sis?

364
00:17:24,230 --> 00:17:25,690
Would you really bury him?

365
00:17:26,150 --> 00:17:26,950
Anytime.

366
00:17:28,110 --> 00:17:29,990
Even if the president forbade it?

367
00:17:30,270 --> 00:17:31,850
And why would the president forbid her?

368
00:17:32,950 --> 00:17:35,050
I don't know, what if you attacked Prague.

369
00:17:36,150 --> 00:17:38,050
Lexa could never pull that off.

370
00:17:39,050 --> 00:17:39,950
What are you talking about?

371
00:17:40,150 --> 00:17:40,560
Easy.

372
00:17:40,950 --> 00:17:42,600
And why would you do that?

373
00:17:42,750 --> 00:17:43,850
If it pissed me off.

374
00:17:44,450 --> 00:17:46,550
Lexa, you said the same about Horacek.

375
00:17:47,050 --> 00:17:48,250
He hasn't pissed me off yet.

376
00:17:49,150 --> 00:17:52,850
Not even when he stuck a note on your back saying "king of all queers" yesterday?

377
00:17:54,440 --> 00:17:55,780
Lexa, some hero you are.

378
00:17:55,780 --> 00:18:00,650
I'm not starting anything when I know you wouldn't even bury me.

379
00:18:03,850 --> 00:18:05,650
Hey, you really wouldn't bury him?

380
00:18:06,350 --> 00:18:08,150
I don't know, it's tough.

381
00:18:11,550 --> 00:18:13,950
We should probably bury relatives, right?

382
00:18:15,050 --> 00:18:16,350
Relatives especially.

383
00:18:30,350 --> 00:18:31,950
So what about the burying?

384
00:18:34,950 --> 00:18:38,050
Well, I'd bury him if it wasn't forbidden.

385
00:18:39,150 --> 00:18:40,350
Who's forbidding you?

386
00:18:40,560 --> 00:18:41,140
The president.

387
00:18:42,720 --> 00:18:43,300
What?

388
00:18:43,950 --> 00:18:47,550
He's not forbidding me now, but if he did, what could I do?

389
00:18:49,350 --> 00:18:51,900
Why would the president forbid you from burying Lexa?

390
00:18:51,900 --> 00:18:53,080
If I attacked Prague.

391
00:18:55,050 --> 00:18:59,250
Lexa, you're not planning to do something stupid, are you?

392
00:19:00,450 --> 00:19:01,250
Not yet.

393
00:19:01,460 --> 00:19:02,040
Good.

394
00:19:03,650 --> 00:19:06,050
Now listen carefully, I won't repeat this twice.

395
00:19:07,050 --> 00:19:09,950
Don't get into big stuff, leave that to politicians.

396
00:19:10,350 --> 00:19:11,550
Stick to smaller things.

397
00:19:11,650 --> 00:19:12,780
Like Uncle Horvat.

398
00:19:13,250 --> 00:19:16,250
There's no shame in it and you can still make a buck.

399
00:19:16,400 --> 00:19:16,880
Got it?

400
00:19:19,550 --> 00:19:21,750
So, burying is allowed, but watch out for the president, got it?

401
00:19:23,590 --> 00:19:24,070
What?

402
00:19:24,150 --> 00:19:25,150
Why watch the president?

403
00:19:25,230 --> 00:19:25,850
Hello.

404
00:19:26,010 --> 00:19:26,470
Say hello.

405
00:19:28,630 --> 00:19:29,110
Say hello.

406
00:19:31,850 --> 00:19:32,550
What do you want?

407
00:19:33,850 --> 00:19:36,250
I just came to let you know she's no longer my sister.

408
00:19:36,430 --> 00:19:37,570
I went to the registry office.

409
00:19:37,570 --> 00:19:39,250
What a relief.

410
00:19:39,650 --> 00:19:40,790
Wait, what do you mean?

411
00:19:40,850 --> 00:19:42,650
If you hadn't gone, I'd have had to go myself.

412
00:19:42,750 --> 00:19:45,410
Well, I'm surprised you're being so reasonable.

413
00:19:45,650 --> 00:19:47,310
Could you pay Ozzak's tab?

414
00:19:47,650 --> 00:19:48,750
But it's only the fourth, right?

415
00:19:48,750 --> 00:19:49,410
Just in case.

416
00:19:49,570 --> 00:19:50,690
Wait, just in case?

417
00:19:50,690 --> 00:19:54,750
How do I know if tomorrow Ozzak won't stop seeming like a good enough brother too?

418
00:19:55,050 --> 00:19:56,950
Good Lord, what's gotten into all of you?

419
00:19:57,150 --> 00:19:57,650
Fine, a man died, it's sad, I get it.

420
00:19:59,710 --> 00:20:01,590
He was your friend, you loved him.

421
00:20:02,050 --> 00:20:05,450
But for me he was a complete stranger, you understand?

422
00:20:06,350 --> 00:20:08,690
You can say that after everything he did for you.

423
00:20:08,870 --> 00:20:09,910
And what did he do for me?

424
00:20:09,910 --> 00:20:16,350
And who do you think went to Ozzak and told him you're all alone with a little girl, so he should get a decent job and come help you?

425
00:20:17,210 --> 00:20:17,630
Prase?

426
00:20:17,630 --> 00:20:19,350
Well, who else?

427
00:20:20,350 --> 00:20:23,180
Do you know why Ozzak had Prase registered as family?

428
00:20:23,350 --> 00:20:25,120
To annoy me, probably.

429
00:20:25,250 --> 00:20:28,450
No, so Prase could pick up Iva from kindergarten.

430
00:20:30,000 --> 00:20:30,420
What?

431
00:20:30,750 --> 00:20:32,050
Well, occasionally, you know.

432
00:20:32,110 --> 00:20:32,530
Yeah.

433
00:20:33,050 --> 00:20:37,050
Since then Ozzak was afraid she might fall into something again, so Prase would pick her up.

434
00:20:37,350 --> 00:20:39,900
He'd always bring her here and from here Ozzak would walk her home.

435
00:20:39,900 --> 00:20:42,120
And why didn't you tell me?

436
00:20:42,120 --> 00:20:44,180
I could have found a babysitter.

437
00:20:44,450 --> 00:20:45,850
And you wouldn't be ashamed?

438
00:20:46,050 --> 00:20:48,550
Entrusting a child to a stranger?

439
00:20:54,000 --> 00:20:54,700
Hello.

440
00:20:55,650 --> 00:20:56,750
Are you having a good day?

441
00:20:58,650 --> 00:20:59,550
Certainly.

442
00:20:59,650 --> 00:21:03,810
The sun is shining, clear blue sky, lilies are blooming.

443
00:21:04,150 --> 00:21:05,410
Is Mr. Pacovsky here?

444
00:21:05,410 --> 00:21:06,310
Why do you ask?

445
00:21:07,850 --> 00:21:12,250
Where I come from, answering a question with a question is considered pathetic.

446
00:21:12,260 --> 00:21:13,140
Big deal.

447
00:21:13,140 --> 00:21:16,550
Trivialization won't work on me.

448
00:21:17,550 --> 00:21:19,550
I'm just trying to find out who you are.

449
00:21:20,050 --> 00:21:21,520
And what business is it of yours?

450
00:21:21,650 --> 00:21:25,050
I always do that when I see a suspicious individual.

451
00:21:25,950 --> 00:21:26,520
That was an insult.

452
00:21:26,520 --> 00:21:26,760
Yes.

453
00:21:29,750 --> 00:21:31,050
I apologize.

454
00:21:31,550 --> 00:21:32,550
Let's start over.

455
00:21:33,650 --> 00:21:34,050
Very well.

456
00:21:35,000 --> 00:21:35,820
Hello.

457
00:21:35,900 --> 00:21:36,260
Hello.

458
00:21:36,500 --> 00:21:38,060
Is Mr. Pacovsky here, please?

459
00:21:38,220 --> 00:21:38,860
Why do you ask?

460
00:21:40,080 --> 00:21:42,040
You're answering with a question again.

461
00:21:42,240 --> 00:21:42,920
Big deal.

462
00:21:43,920 --> 00:21:45,220
May I know your name?

463
00:21:45,360 --> 00:21:47,680
I won't stand for this confrontational style.

464
00:21:47,680 --> 00:21:49,920
You're the one who started this confrontational style.

465
00:21:50,440 --> 00:21:51,640
Don't interrupt me.

466
00:21:52,750 --> 00:21:53,450
I'm leaving.

467
00:21:54,050 --> 00:21:57,460
I'm not wasting my time with some shrieking harpy.

468
00:21:57,550 --> 00:21:58,650
That was an insult.

469
00:21:59,350 --> 00:22:01,050
And that was a mistake.

470
00:22:02,950 --> 00:22:04,950
Would you like to add anything?

471
00:22:06,150 --> 00:22:06,650
No.

472
00:22:09,650 --> 00:22:13,450
So now you're going to apologize nicely.

473
00:22:13,800 --> 00:22:15,700
Otherwise I'll slam you to the ground right here.

474
00:22:16,460 --> 00:22:17,520
That was a mistake.

475
00:22:18,550 --> 00:22:21,950
You're using a threat you can't follow through on.

476
00:22:24,750 --> 00:22:28,610
Stehno doesn't teach this, but two years of judo aren't forgotten.

477
00:22:29,850 --> 00:22:32,150
Wait, you know Dr. Stehno?

478
00:22:32,150 --> 00:22:33,450
Of course.

479
00:22:33,950 --> 00:22:38,950
But he's my guru, I've been studying with him for ten years.

480
00:22:41,050 --> 00:22:42,850
I'm just a beginner.

481
00:22:42,910 --> 00:22:44,330
But you've got talent.

482
00:22:45,950 --> 00:22:46,950
What type are you?

483
00:22:47,550 --> 00:22:51,650
I started as a banana, but I'm already a cucumber.

484
00:22:58,020 --> 00:22:58,540
Kohlrabi.

485
00:22:58,950 --> 00:23:00,550
How did you manage that?

486
00:23:01,250 --> 00:23:04,040
I also took the unbearable assertiveness course.

487
00:23:04,040 --> 00:23:04,400
I see.

488
00:23:05,450 --> 00:23:06,830
So where is Mr. Pacovsky?

489
00:23:06,830 --> 00:23:07,430
Why do you ask?

490
00:23:07,850 --> 00:23:10,930
I came to inform him that we're a funeral home, not a charity.

491
00:23:10,930 --> 00:23:11,590
Big deal.

492
00:23:12,650 --> 00:23:13,650
Trivialization?

493
00:23:20,750 --> 00:23:22,750
I had no idea he sent so many.

494
00:23:23,050 --> 00:23:25,040
It was his dream during communism, you know.

495
00:23:25,350 --> 00:23:30,420
When freedom comes, return all the empty bottles, go abroad and taste every beer in the world.

496
00:23:30,420 --> 00:23:31,960
And Prase did it.

497
00:23:32,420 --> 00:23:33,500
France, champagne.

498
00:23:33,850 --> 00:23:38,750
The beer here is light, sweet and they sell it in 700ml bottles with a cork.

499
00:23:39,150 --> 00:23:40,350
I'm having a great time.

500
00:23:40,950 --> 00:23:42,050
Kisses, Ozzak.

501
00:23:42,240 --> 00:23:42,760
Prase.

502
00:23:44,150 --> 00:23:46,150
You really don't remember him?

503
00:23:46,220 --> 00:23:47,040
Not a clue.

504
00:23:48,650 --> 00:23:49,750
But what about this?

505
00:23:51,750 --> 00:23:52,960
That is, I know that.

506
00:23:53,150 --> 00:23:54,750
Of course, you painted it.

507
00:23:55,050 --> 00:23:56,110
That's us?

508
00:23:56,310 --> 00:23:57,850
Sure, you painted it when he left.

509
00:23:57,890 --> 00:23:58,930
You missed him terribly.

510
00:23:59,450 --> 00:24:01,650
Wait, wait, I remember something.

511
00:24:03,050 --> 00:24:04,550
We went to see him off.

512
00:24:05,650 --> 00:24:08,980
I waved for a really long time and then my arm hurt.

513
00:24:09,350 --> 00:24:13,050
Because nothing stopped him for five hours, even though we were using you as bait.

514
00:24:14,250 --> 00:24:17,710
But he said he'd be right back, that he was just going to Zatec to check on the hops.

515
00:24:19,450 --> 00:24:20,750
He fibbed a little, otherwise you wouldn't have stopped crying.

516
00:24:21,350 --> 00:24:23,050
He always understood kids better than me.

517
00:24:23,350 --> 00:24:28,500
He said you'd be sad for a while, then it would pass quickly, that little kids are like that, and you'd soon forget him.

518
00:24:28,500 --> 00:24:29,980
But he'd never forget you.

519
00:24:31,850 --> 00:24:33,050
The funeral is tomorrow.

520
00:24:33,920 --> 00:24:35,420
Somehow they worked it out with Dad.

521
00:24:35,540 --> 00:24:37,460
It won't be fancy, they say category C minus.

522
00:24:37,720 --> 00:24:38,240
What's that?

523
00:24:38,650 --> 00:24:41,350
Burlap sack, boxers, undershirt, sandals.

524
00:24:41,840 --> 00:24:43,080
But he wouldn't mind.

525
00:24:43,240 --> 00:24:44,260
He dressed like that even in winter.

526
00:24:44,850 --> 00:24:45,850
He was modest.

527
00:24:46,650 --> 00:24:47,650
I'll show you something.

528
00:24:50,150 --> 00:24:50,850
For tomorrow.

529
00:24:51,350 --> 00:24:52,650
Oh, Ivuska.

530
00:24:53,450 --> 00:24:54,660
Won't Dad be mad?

531
00:24:54,850 --> 00:24:56,420
A brother has to be buried.

532
00:24:56,650 --> 00:24:58,050
That's been known for thousands of years.

533
00:25:16,640 --> 00:25:17,640
Hi, Ivuska.

534
00:25:18,000 --> 00:25:19,900
Well, you look nice.

535
00:25:20,340 --> 00:25:20,780
Thanks.

536
00:25:20,920 --> 00:25:21,740
You too.

537
00:25:24,650 --> 00:25:27,760
Ozzak, can I really come even though I'm not family?

538
00:25:27,850 --> 00:25:30,450
Sure, the more women in black, the better.

539
00:25:31,450 --> 00:25:32,550
Prase loved looking at them.

540
00:25:32,750 --> 00:25:34,850
They reminded him of waitresses.

541
00:25:38,550 --> 00:25:40,620
Right folks, everything's ready.

542
00:25:40,620 --> 00:25:42,520
Mrs. Marta has been warming up since morning.

543
00:25:42,540 --> 00:25:46,540
She's had two bottles of wine already, so she's getting quite tolerant.

544
00:25:46,660 --> 00:25:49,820
Just a small thing to set the mood.

545
00:25:53,650 --> 00:25:56,450
I wouldn't do this, but the boss insists.

546
00:25:57,050 --> 00:25:58,630
We're supposed to put these on now?

547
00:25:58,950 --> 00:26:00,050
Do you have a problem with that?

548
00:26:00,090 --> 00:26:00,850
Big deal.

549
00:26:01,850 --> 00:26:03,230
I'll kick you into a ball.

550
00:26:03,450 --> 00:26:04,950
And I'll roll you away.

551
00:26:06,170 --> 00:26:06,750
Fine.

552
00:26:11,350 --> 00:26:14,260
All right, bro, if you really haven't changed your mind.

553
00:26:14,550 --> 00:26:16,150
I don't know him that well.

554
00:26:17,050 --> 00:26:19,250
Mom, so we painted those signs for nothing.

555
00:26:19,580 --> 00:26:20,480
What signs?

556
00:26:31,580 --> 00:26:32,380
So?

557
00:26:33,950 --> 00:26:35,050
How was the funeral?

558
00:26:36,560 --> 00:26:37,140
Unbelievable.

559
00:26:38,050 --> 00:26:38,800
Three hundred people.

560
00:26:39,350 --> 00:26:40,220
And Mrs. Marta?

561
00:26:40,220 --> 00:26:41,900
Man, what an old cobra.

562
00:26:42,580 --> 00:26:45,240
She rocked it with the Brutus songs, man.

563
00:26:45,280 --> 00:26:47,480
By the chorus the whole crematorium was moshing.

564
00:26:48,650 --> 00:26:50,450
And then the wreaths started catching fire.

565
00:26:51,250 --> 00:26:52,750
I cried like a baby.

566
00:26:53,750 --> 00:26:55,650
So what brings you to the Badger?

567
00:26:56,350 --> 00:26:58,450
I needed to ask you something.

568
00:26:59,790 --> 00:27:00,430
Yeah?

569
00:27:02,950 --> 00:27:13,850
You wouldn't happen to have any idea who the mysterious benefactor is who ended up paying for Prase's A-plus funeral, including the glass coffin with handle?

570
00:27:14,720 --> 00:27:15,360
No.

571
00:27:17,950 --> 00:27:20,150
Mrs. Marta let it slip after her third bottle.

572
00:27:20,820 --> 00:27:21,180
Oh.

573
00:27:23,850 --> 00:27:24,350
Thanks.

574
00:27:25,060 --> 00:27:25,900
You're a brother.

575
00:27:26,100 --> 00:27:26,460
Yeah.

576
00:27:29,550 --> 00:27:32,550
Come on, stop it, you're the king of all queers after all.

577
00:27:32,850 --> 00:27:34,650
So you really are going to stay brothers.

578
00:27:35,390 --> 00:27:36,970
I hope you're not dipping into Ozzak's savings too, are you?

579
00:27:37,090 --> 00:27:38,270
Prase wouldn't like that.

580
00:27:38,450 --> 00:27:40,210
No, I had something set aside for a funeral.

581
00:27:40,470 --> 00:27:41,050
For your own?

582
00:27:41,210 --> 00:27:41,470
Yeah.

583
00:27:41,950 --> 00:27:42,650
Wow.

584
00:27:43,250 --> 00:27:46,750
Well bro, if you kick the bucket before you save up again, I'll sell the coasters.

585
00:27:48,550 --> 00:27:49,750
So I really am a brother.

586
00:27:51,250 --> 00:27:51,850
Well, thanks.

587
00:27:52,750 --> 00:27:54,550
Things are probably getting started at Simona's.

588
00:27:56,350 --> 00:27:59,950
Feel like hitting the town?

589
00:28:01,650 --> 00:28:02,850
Let's pig out like Prase.

590
00:28:34,050 --> 00:28:35,850
So, to brotherhood.

591
00:28:37,480 --> 00:28:38,620
And nothing for little sister?

592
00:28:48,330 --> 00:28:49,390
I'm putting it on your tab, okay?

593
00:28:49,590 --> 00:28:51,130
No, he can't be short on cash right now.

594
00:28:51,470 --> 00:28:52,110
Add it on, right?

595
00:28:53,250 --> 00:28:54,550
Man, bro.

596
00:28:55,150 --> 00:28:57,050
You talk just like Prase.

597
00:28:57,350 --> 00:28:59,150
One more round then.
